  <!-- ============================================================
       USE CASES — "three examples, one pattern"
       Quiet, grounded, relatable. Each is a real piece of work most
       businesses need but can't justify a full-time hire for.
       ============================================================ -->
  <section class="concept-section concept-usecase" aria-labelledby="usecaseTitle">
    <div class="concept-section__inner">
      <div class="concept-section__head">
        <p class="label label--accent">Three examples. One pattern.</p>
        <h2 id="usecaseTitle" class="concept-section__title">
          Work you can't justify <em>a full hire for.</em>
        </h2>
        <p class="concept-section__lede">
          Below are three pieces of work every business needs done. Each one is too small
          for a full-time hire, too important to keep ignoring, and too easy to forget
          until the moment it's already cost you. They share the same shape — and the
          same solution.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- USE CASE 1 — after-hours customer email -->
      <div class="concept-usecase__case">
        <h3 class="concept-usecase__case-title">A customer emails you <em>at 11 p.m. Tuesday.</em></h3>
        <div class="concept-usecase__grid">
          <div class="concept-usecase__col">
            <p class="concept-usecase__col-label">Today</p>
            <p class="concept-usecase__col-body">
              The email sits in your inbox until morning. By the time you reply, the customer
              has already emailed two of your competitors. The one who answered first wins.
              You couldn't have stayed up to catch it, and you couldn't afford to hire someone
              who would.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="concept-usecase__col concept-usecase__col--db">
            <p class="concept-usecase__col-label concept-usecase__col-label--accent">With DREAMBORN</p>
            <p class="concept-usecase__col-body">
              An agent on your roster reads the email at 11:02 p.m. It pulls the invoice from
              your records, drafts a clear response, sends it, and writes a receipt your team
              reviews in the morning. The customer's question is answered in minutes. Your
              evening is your own.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- USE CASE 2 — weekly competitive analysis -->
      <div class="concept-usecase__case">
        <h3 class="concept-usecase__case-title">You haven't checked your competitor's pricing <em>in weeks.</em></h3>
        <div class="concept-usecase__grid">
          <div class="concept-usecase__col">
            <p class="concept-usecase__col-label">Today</p>
            <p class="concept-usecase__col-body">
              Your top competitor changed three pricing tiers last Tuesday. You found out
              from a prospect asking why your plan costs $200 more. A market analyst would
              run you eighty thousand a year — and even then they'd catch maybe sixty percent
              of what actually moves a deal.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="concept-usecase__col concept-usecase__col--db">
            <p class="concept-usecase__col-label concept-usecase__col-label--accent">With DREAMBORN</p>
            <p class="concept-usecase__col-body">
              An agent visits your competitor every Monday at 6 a.m. — pricing page, new
              features, customer reviews, hiring postings, recent press. By 7 a.m. a
              one-page brief is on your desk. Differences from last week are flagged.
              Anything that moves your needle is at the top of your inbox before your
              first meeting.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- USE CASE 3 — weekly sales report -->
      <div class="concept-usecase__case">
        <h3 class="concept-usecase__case-title">The pipeline report <em>nobody reads.</em></h3>
        <div class="concept-usecase__grid">
          <div class="concept-usecase__col">
            <p class="concept-usecase__col-label">Today</p>
            <p class="concept-usecase__col-body">
              Your CRM has a pipeline dashboard. It's too dense to read in under twenty
              minutes. Friday afternoon, someone exports CSVs, opens Excel, makes pivot
              tables, sends a PDF nobody opens. By Monday morning, decisions are being
              made on gut and last week's coincidences.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="concept-usecase__col concept-usecase__col--db">
            <p class="concept-usecase__col-label concept-usecase__col-label--accent">With DREAMBORN</p>
            <p class="concept-usecase__col-body">
              An agent watches your CRM, your call recordings, your email threads. Every
              Sunday evening it ships you a one-page chart: what closed, what slipped,
              what's stuck, who you should call this week. No CSVs. No pivot tables.
              Just signal — and the receipts to back it up.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="concept-usecase__close">
        Three examples, one shape. You couldn't justify hiring an overnight support
        specialist, a dedicated competitive analyst, or a full-time pipeline auditor.
        You can justify an agent for each. The same pattern applies to inbound triage,
        contract review, customer onboarding, knowledge base maintenance, status reporting,
        and the dozens of other quiet jobs your business needs done. Each one a seat at
        your table that wasn't worth filling — until now.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

